The statement "If Jane studied, then she did not study long" can be logically represented as "Jane studied ⊃ ¬(Jane studied long)".

To determine if we can infer "If Jane studied long, then she did not study", we need to check if the contrapositive of the original statement is logically equivalent to the new statement.

The contrapositive of "Jane studied ⊃ ¬(Jane studied long)" is "¬(Jane studied long) ⊃ ¬(Jane studied)".

Therefore, we can infer "If Jane studied long, then she did not study" if and only if "If Jane did not study long, then she did not study".

Answer: No, we cannot infer "If Jane studied long, then she did not study" from "If Jane studied, then she did not study long".
